The discriminant of this quadratic equation is: \[ D = 4(a + 2)^2 \] For the quadratic to have two distinct real roots, \( a \neq -2 \). We need both roots of the quadratic to lie within \((-1, 1)\). This requires: 1. The quadratic to be positive at \( t = -1 \) and \( t = 1 \). 2. The roots to be within the interval \((-1, 1)\). Evaluating the quadratic at \( t = -1 \) and \( t = 1 \): \[ f(-1) = 3 + a \] \[ f(1) = 3 - 3a \] For both values to be positive: \[ 3 + a > 0 \implies a > -3 \] \[ 3 - 3a > 0 \implies a < 1 \] Thus, \( a \) must lie in the interval \((-3, 1)\). Excluding \( a = -2 \) (where the quadratic has a double root), the set of \( a \) is: \[ (-3, -2) \cup (-2, 1) \] The values \( p = -3 \), \( q = -2 \), and \( r = 1 \) give: \[ p + q + r = -3 + (-2) + 1 = -4 \] \[ \boxed{-4} \]
